+# DMS Integration into vLLM v0.17.1 — Implementation Notes
+
+## vLLM Architecture Overview (relevant parts)
+
+vLLM v0.17.1 uses a **v1 engine** architecture. The key subsystems are:
+
+1. **Model layer** — per-model attention implementation (e.g. `Qwen3Attention`)
+2. **Attention abstraction** — backend-agnostic `Attention` layer that dispatches to FlashAttention/FlashInfer/etc.
+3. **KV cache** — paged block-based storage, managed by `BlockPool` and `KVCacheManager`
+4. **Scheduler** — decides which requests to run, allocates blocks, handles preemption
+5. **Model runner** — orchestrates forward pass, builds metadata, manages GPU tensors
+
+---
+
+## File Map — What Needs Touching
+
+### Tier 1: Must change
+
+| File | What | Why |
+|------|------|-----|
+| `vllm/model_executor/models/qwen3.py` | `Qwen3Attention.forward()` | Extract eviction decision from query projection (last dim of first Q head per GQA group), zero it out, pass decisions downstream |
+| `vllm/v1/attention/backends/flash_attn.py` | `FlashAttentionImpl.forward()` and `do_kv_cache_update()` | During decode: standard flash_attn on compressed cache (already works). During prefill: need DMS-masked attention (new kernel or FlexAttn path). Cache update must handle slot recycling based on eviction decisions |
+| `vllm/v1/worker/block_table.py` | `BlockTable` and slot mapping | Need to track per-layer (or per-head) effective sequence lengths. Slot mapping must support overwriting evicted slots rather than only appending |
+| `vllm/v1/core/single_type_kv_cache_manager.py` | `get_num_blocks_to_allocate()` | Memory estimation must account for compression — fewer blocks needed than `ceil(num_tokens / block_size)` |
+
+### Tier 2: Likely changes
+
+| File | What | Why |
+|------|------|-----|
+| `vllm/v1/core/sched/scheduler.py` | `Scheduler.schedule()` | Memory-aware scheduling should use compressed cache sizes. Currently assumes `num_blocks = ceil(tokens / block_size)` |
+| `vllm/v1/core/block_pool.py` | `BlockPool` | May need partial-block freeing or at minimum tracking of how full each block is after eviction |
+| `vllm/v1/kv_cache_interface.py` | `FullAttentionSpec` | Add DMS config parameters (window_size, compression_ratio) to cache spec so backends know about DMS |
+| `vllm/v1/attention/backend.py` | `AttentionImpl` interface | May need to extend `forward()` signature or metadata to carry eviction decisions |
+| `vllm/forward_context.py` | `ForwardContext` | Carry DMS state (eviction decisions, circular buffer) through the forward pass |
+| `vllm/config/cache.py` | `CacheConfig` | Add DMS-specific config: `dms_window_size`, `dms_compression_ratio`, `dms_alpha_per` |
+
+### Tier 3: Maybe / nice-to-have
+
+| File | What | Why |
+|------|------|-----|
+| `vllm/model_executor/models/registry.py` | Model registry | Register DMS variant if not using plugin system |
+| `vllm/v1/attention/backends/flex_attention.py` | FlexAttention backend | Already exists in vLLM — could be extended with DMS score_mod for prefill |
+| `vllm/v1/attention/ops/triton_reshape_and_cache_flash.py` | Triton cache write kernel | If doing in-place slot recycling, this kernel needs to handle overwriting evicted positions |
+| `vllm/v1/worker/gpu_model_runner.py` | `execute_model()` | May need to pass DMS metadata into forward context |
+
+---
+
+## Design Decisions
+
+### Per-layer vs per-head
+
+**Per-layer** (`dms_alpha_per='layer'`): All heads in a layer share the same eviction decisions and cache length. Fits vLLM's existing assumptions (block tables are per-KV-cache-group, not per-head). One eviction decision per layer per token.
+
+**Per-head** (`dms_alpha_per='head'`): Each head independently decides which tokens to evict. This is what the published checkpoint and all paper results use. Requires the batch×head flattening trick for block tables, slot mapping, and seq lengths (see "Per-Head Mode: Detailed Analysis" section below).
+
+### Where to extract the eviction signal
+
+DMS repurposes the last dimension of the first query head per GQA group. The insertion point is: after any per-head normalization of Q, before RoPE. The decision dimension must be zeroed out before rotary embedding contaminates it.
+
+**Example: Qwen3** (the model has `q_norm`/`k_norm` RMSNorm before RoPE — confirmed in HF DMS model `modeling_qwen3_dms.py` line 96):
+
+```python
+qkv, _ = self.qkv_proj(hidden_states)
+q, k, v = qkv.split([self.q_size, self.kv_size, self.kv_size], dim=-1)
+
+# q_norm FIRST (decision logits are extracted post-norm)
+q_reshaped = q.view(-1, self.num_heads, self.head_dim)
+q_reshaped = self.q_norm(q_reshaped)
+
+# --- DMS: extract and zero decision logit ---
+q_per_kv = self.num_heads // self.num_kv_heads
+decision_logits = q_reshaped[:, ::q_per_kv, -1].clone() * decision_scale - decision_offset
+decisions = (decision_logits > 0).float()  # [num_tokens, num_kv_heads]
+q_reshaped[:, ::q_per_kv, -1] = 0  # zero out before RoPE
+q = q_reshaped.view(-1, self.num_heads * self.head_dim)
+# --- end DMS ---
+
+k = self.k_norm(k.view(..., self.head_dim)).view(k.shape)
+q, k = self.rotary_emb(positions, q, k)
+attn_output = self.attn(q, k, v, dms_decisions=decisions)
+```
+
+For models without `q_norm` (e.g. Llama), extraction goes directly after the Q/K/V split.
+
+### How to handle the cache update
+
+**Decode (token-by-token):**
+The existing repos show that decode is simple — evicted tokens are already gone from the cache, so standard `flash_attn_with_kvcache` works. The new part is the bookkeeping:
+
+1. Each decode step produces an eviction decision for the *previous* token (shift-by-one)
+2. That decision enters a circular window buffer of size `dms_window_size`
+3. When a token exits the window and is marked for eviction, its cache slot is freed
+4. The new token overwrites the freed slot (or appends if no eviction)
+
+This circular buffer state needs to live somewhere accessible during the forward pass. Options:
+- **On the `ForwardContext`**: passed through `set_forward_context()`
+- **On the model layer**: store as a buffer on `Qwen3Attention`, similar to how RoPE cache works
+- **On a new `DMSCacheManager`**: separate object that wraps or extends the existing cache
+
+**Prefill:**
+Prefill is harder. The model must process the full prompt while applying DMS eviction decisions to the attention mask. Three approaches, ordered by implementation difficulty:
+
+1. **Two-pass prefill** (simplest, slowest): Standard prefill first, then extract decisions and compact the cache. Decode proceeds on the compressed cache. No custom kernel needed but doubles prefill cost.
+
+2. **FlexAttention with DMS score_mod** (moderate): vLLM already has a `flex_attention.py` backend. Extend it with a DMS `score_mod` that applies `log(1 - α)` masking. Model Optimizer's `attention_prefill.py` is the reference. Requires the FlexAttention backend to be production-quality in vLLM (check status).
+
+3. **Custom Triton prefill kernel** (best performance): kvcompress's `dms_fused_prefill` shows this is feasible — pre-compute all eviction decisions, single kernel launch with DMS visibility rule. Most work but best TTFT.
+
+### Scheduler changes
+
+The scheduler currently estimates memory as `num_blocks = ceil(num_tokens / block_size)`. With DMS, actual blocks used will be ~`ceil(num_tokens / (block_size * CR))` at steady state, but compression ratio varies:
+- Short sequences: CR closer to 1x (little compression)
+- Long sequences: CR exceeds target (more aggressive compression)
+- Early layers: less compression than later layers
+
+The scheduler needs to track `actual_blocks_used` per (request, head), updated each step from the DMS circular buffer state. Freed blocks go back to the pool. Scheduling decisions use actual compressed sizes instead of the theoretical maximum.
+
+---
+
+## Modularity Strategy
+
+Goal: minimize diff against upstream vLLM so it's maintainable across versions.
+
+### Model-agnostic DMS core (following Model Optimizer's pattern)
+
+Model Optimizer's ARCHITECTURE.md explicitly separates DMS into model-agnostic and model-specific code. The core operations — `prepare_attention_input`, `dms_attention`, `post_process_attention_output` — work with any model that provides Q/K/V projections. Adding a new model family is just 4 files under `models/your_model/`.
+
+The same pattern should apply in vLLM:
+
+- **Model-agnostic DMS utilities** (shared): Decision extraction from query tensor, shift-by-one logic, circular buffer management, slot recycling, DMS-masked prefill. These don't depend on Qwen3 — they work with any GQA model.
+- **Model-specific thin layer** (per model): Override attention forward to call the shared DMS utilities. For Qwen3 this is mostly `q[:, ::q_per_kv, -1]` extraction and zeroing. For Llama or any other GQA model, it would be near-identical.
+
+This means the vLLM integration shouldn't be "Qwen3 DMS support" — it should be "DMS attention backend that any model can opt into", with model-specific files that are mostly boilerplate.
+
+### Approach: DMS as an attention backend + model variant
+
+1. **DMS utilities** (`vllm/v1/attention/dms/` or similar):
+   - `dms_state.py` — `DMSState` class: circular buffer, eviction tracking, slot recycling logic. Model-agnostic — operates on tensors of decisions and cache positions.
+   - `dms_prefill.py` — DMS-masked prefill (FlexAttn score_mod or Triton kernel). Model-agnostic — takes decision logits and produces masked attention output.
+
+2. **New attention backend** (`vllm/v1/attention/backends/dms_flash_attn.py`):
+   - Extends `FlashAttentionImpl`
+   - Overrides `do_kv_cache_update()` to handle slot recycling via `DMSState`
+   - Overrides `forward()` to apply DMS masking during prefill
+   - Decode path delegates to standard flash attention (no change needed)
+   - Any GQA model can use this backend — not Qwen3-specific
+
+3. **Model file per architecture** (`vllm/model_executor/models/qwen3_dms.py`):
+   - Inherits from `Qwen3ForCausalLM`
+   - Overrides `Qwen3Attention` with `Qwen3DMSAttention` that extracts eviction signal and passes it to the DMS backend
+   - Registers in model registry via plugin or direct registration
+   - Loads DMS config params from HuggingFace `config.json`
+   - Adding Llama DMS, Mistral DMS, etc. would be a similar small file each
+   - **Note:** The only truly model-specific part is where in the forward pass to call the extraction (e.g. after `q_norm` for Qwen3, directly after split for Llama). This could be reduced to a single registered callable/hook per architecture instead of a full model subclass, avoiding per-model file duplication entirely.
+
+4. **Config extension** (minimal changes to existing files):
+   - Add `dms_window_size`, `dms_compression_ratio` to `CacheConfig` or a new `DMSConfig`
+   - Plumb through to attention backend selection
+
+5. **Scheduler hook** (small change):
+   - After each step, update request block counts from actual DMS state
+   - Free excess blocks
+
+This keeps the core vLLM changes to:
+- A few lines in `CacheConfig` for new params
+- A few lines in the model registry
+- A scheduler hook for block count updates
+- Everything else is in new files
+
+### Files that stay UNTOUCHED with this approach
+
+- `block_pool.py` — block allocation/freeing API doesn't change, just called differently
+- `kv_cache_manager.py` — block counts updated externally
+- `backend.py` — new backend implements existing interface
+- `gpu_model_runner.py` — forward context already extensible
+- Core attention ops — decode uses existing flash_attn unchanged
+
+---
+
+## Implementation Order
+
+### Phase 1: Per-head decode + two-pass prefill
+
+1. Add DMS config params (`dms_window_size`, `decision_scale`, `initial_decision_offset`) — read from HF `config.json`, plumb to `CacheConfig` or new `DMSConfig`
+2. Per-head block table and slot mapping plumbing in `block_table.py`: block table shape `(num_reqs * num_kv_heads, max_blocks)`, seq_lens shape `(batch_size * num_kv_heads,)`, per-head slot mapping
+3. Resolve per-head cache writes: extend `reshape_and_cache` kernel for per-head slot_mapping, or bypass it using `flash_attn_with_kvcache`'s built-in cache write (as Model Optimizer does)
+4. Create model-agnostic `DMSState` class: circular buffer per `(batch, head)`, eviction tracking, slot recycling (batch×head flattening trick)
+5. Create `dms_flash_attn.py` backend: per-head block tables, per-head seq lengths, decode via standard `flash_attn_with_kvcache` on flattened batch×head dimension
+6. Create `qwen3_dms.py` model: eviction signal extraction (reads DMS config from step 1), passes decisions to DMS backend
+7. Register model in registry
+8. Two-pass prefill: standard prefill writes all tokens to cache, then compact per-head — determine survivors from eviction decisions, copy surviving KV pairs into per-head block tables, free original full blocks, update per-head seq_lens
+9. **Test:** Load Qwen3-8B-DMS-8x checkpoint (per-head), generate text, verify eviction happens and output quality matches HF baseline
+
+### Phase 2: Scheduler integration
+
+1. Track actual compressed block counts per (request, head)
+2. Free excess blocks after each step
+3. Update scheduler memory estimation for per-head varying lengths
+4. **Test:** Run with concurrent requests, verify higher throughput than vanilla at same VRAM
+
+### Phase 3: Optimized prefill
+
+1. Either FlexAttention score_mod or custom Triton kernel for DMS-masked prefill with per-head masking
+2. **Test:** Measure TTFT improvement over two-pass approach
+
+---
+
+## Per-Head Mode: Detailed Analysis
+
+### The batch×head flattening trick (from Model Optimizer / kvcompress)
+
+The existing DMS repos already solve per-head decode with standard `flash_attn_with_kvcache` — **no custom attention kernel needed**. The trick: flatten `(batch, num_kv_heads)` into a single "page_batch" dimension.
+
+From Model Optimizer's `cache_paged.py`:
+```python
+self.page_batch = self.batch_size * self.num_heads
+```
+
+Then everything is indexed by `page_batch` instead of `batch`:
+- `block_table`: shape `(batch * num_kv_heads, max_blocks_per_head)` — per-head blocks
+- `cache_seq_lengths`: shape `(batch * num_kv_heads,)` — per-head lengths
+- `recent_info`: shape `(batch * num_kv_heads, window_size, 2)` — per-head circular buffer
+
+When calling `flash_attn_with_kvcache` for decode:
+- `q` reshaped from `(batch, num_q_heads, 1, head_dim)` to `(batch * num_kv_heads, q_per_kv, 1, head_dim)`
+- `cache_seqlens` = `(batch * num_kv_heads,)` — each head has its own length
+- `block_table` = `(batch * num_kv_heads, max_blocks)` — each head has its own blocks
+
+`flash_attn_with_kvcache` doesn't care whether the batch dimension is real batch or batch×heads — it does paged attention per row. This means **decode per-head works with the existing kernel**.
+
+### What actually needs changing in vLLM for per-head
+
+The attention kernel is NOT the blocker. The plumbing around it is:
+
+| Component | Current shape | Per-head shape | Change scope |
+|-----------|--------------|----------------|-------------|
+| `block_table` | `(num_reqs, max_blocks)` | `(num_reqs * num_kv_heads, max_blocks)` | `block_table.py`, metadata |
+| `seq_lens` | `(batch_size,)` | `(batch_size * num_kv_heads,)` | `backend.py`, `flash_attn.py` |
+| `slot_mapping` | `(num_tokens,)` | `(num_tokens * num_kv_heads,)` or `(num_tokens, num_kv_heads)` | `block_table.py`, reshape_and_cache kernel |
+| `reshape_and_cache` | One slot per token for all heads | Per-head slots | Triton kernel rewrite |
+| `BlockPool` / `KVCacheManager` | Track blocks per request | Track blocks per (request, head) | Core data structures |
+| Scheduler | `ceil(tokens / block_size)` per req | Sum across heads, each with different length | `scheduler.py`, memory math |
+| `CommonAttentionMetadata` | Shared across layers | Per-head dimensions | `backend.py`, all backends |
+| Query reshape in forward | `(num_tokens, num_q_heads, head_dim)` | `(num_tokens * num_kv_heads, q_per_kv, head_dim)` | Backend forward methods |
+
+### The real blocker: prefill, not decode
+
+Decode per-head is tractable using the batch×head trick — standard flash_attn works.
+
+**Prefill is the hard part** regardless of per-head or per-layer. `flash_attn_varlen_func` doesn't support per-head variable-length masking or DMS eviction masks. You need one of:
+
+1. **FlexAttention with DMS `score_mod`** — Model Optimizer's approach. `attention_prefill.py` builds a `compressed_attention_mask` per key encoding visibility range, passed to `torch.nn.attention.flex_attention`. vLLM already has a `flex_attention.py` backend that could be extended.
+
+2. **Custom Triton kernel** — kvcompress's approach. `dms_fused_prefill` pre-computes all eviction decisions (possible because eviction is monotonic and independent per token), then launches a single flash attention kernel with the DMS visibility rule: `visible = causal AND (in_window OR NOT evicted)`. ~110 lines of kernel code.
+
+3. **Two-pass** — Standard prefill first, then compact cache based on decisions. Simplest but doubles prefill cost.
+
+Either way, the prefill kernel is needed for both per-layer and per-head. Per-head just adds the batch×head reshape on top.
+
+### Per-head vs per-layer: actual comparison
+
+| Aspect | Per-layer | Per-head |
+|--------|-----------|----------|
+| Decode kernel | Unchanged | Unchanged (batch×head trick) |
+| Prefill kernel | New (DMS mask) | Same new kernel + batch×head reshape |
+| Block table | Unchanged shape | `num_kv_heads` × wider |
+| Slot mapping | Minor (overwrite slots) | Per-head slot maps |
+| Block allocation | Small scheduler hook | `num_kv_heads` × more tracking |
+| KV cache layout | Unchanged | Unchanged (heads already separate dim in blocks) |
+| Memory overhead | Minimal | `num_kv_heads` × block table memory |
+| Scheduler complexity | Low | Medium (per-head block counts) |
+| New files needed | 2 (model + backend) | 2 + edits to block_table.py, cache manager, scheduler |
+| Quality | Unknown (no published data) | Published (paper results) |
+| Upstream maintainability | Plugin-friendly | Larger diff, harder rebase |
+
+### Note
+
+The prefill kernel investment is the same for both modes — build it once, reuse for either.
+
+---
+
+## Additional vLLM Mechanisms Affecting DMS
+
+### Chunked prefill
+
+vLLM supports chunked prefill — long prompts are split into chunks processed across multiple steps. DMS eviction decisions at chunk boundaries need handling: decisions from chunk N apply to tokens in chunk N, but the shift-by-one means the last token of chunk N's decision applies to the first token of chunk N+1. The circular buffer state must persist across chunks.
+
+### AttentionMetadataBuilder pattern
+
+Each attention backend has an `AttentionMetadataBuilder` subclass (e.g. `FlashAttentionMetadataBuilder`) that constructs backend-specific metadata from `CommonAttentionMetadata`. The DMS backend needs its own builder that produces per-head block tables, seq_lens, and slot mappings from the common metadata.
+
+### Cache stride ordering
+
+`get_kv_cache_stride_order()` in `AttentionBackend` (`backend.py`) abstracts memory layout — flash attention uses "NHD" or "HND" layouts. DMS per-head slot mapping must work with whatever layout the backend specifies.
+
+### FP8 KV cache
+
+`reshape_and_cache_kernel_flash` handles FP8 quantization on-the-fly with `k_scale` and `v_scale` parameters. Any per-head extension to this kernel must preserve the FP8 code path.
+
+### DCP/PCP (distributed context parallelism)
+
+`block_table.py` has distributed cache mechanisms (`dcp_local_seq_lens`, `cp_kv_cache_interleave_size`). Slot mapping computation changes for multi-GPU setups (block_table.py lines 144-179). DMS integration with multi-GPU requires separate handling.
+
+### kvcompress: on-read compaction
+
+kvcompress does not compact the cache on write. Instead, `get_contiguous_cache()` (dms_cache.py lines 655-785) remaps positions on read using `recent_info`. This is an alternative to the on-write compaction described in the two-pass prefill approach.
+
+---
+
+## Key Questions — Status
+
+### Resolved
+
+1. **FlexAttention backend maturity** — vLLM's `flex_attention.py` is a full backend (~500 lines) with `torch.compile(flex_attention, fullgraph=True)`, compiled `create_block_mask`, physical-to-logical block mapping, `score_mod` and `mask_mod` support, sliding window, multimodal prefix ranges, cascade attention, and doc-id-based batching. It already accepts custom `score_mod` / `mask_mod` functions. DMS prefill would add a `score_mod` that applies `log(1 - α)` masking per the Model Optimizer pattern.
+
+2. **torch.compile compatibility** — Model Optimizer decorates all core DMS functions with `@torch.compile()`: `prepare_attention_input`, `_aux_update_single`, `post_process_attention_output`, `compiled_flex_attention`, plus `torch._dynamo.config.cache_size_limit = 72`. vLLM also uses `torch.compile` throughout (FlexAttention, FlashAttention graph mode). The DMS operations (decision extraction, circular buffer update, slot recycling) are all tensor ops with no Python control flow dependent on tensor values.
+
+3. **Prefix caching interaction** — `CacheConfig.enable_prefix_caching` (default `True`) is a boolean flag. DMS eviction decisions are per-request, so shared prefix blocks would be mutated differently per request. Setting `enable_prefix_caching=False` for DMS disables this at config level.
+
+### Open
+
+4. **Slot mapping for overwriting evicted slots** — Currently `slot_mapping` is computed as `block_table[req, position // block_size] * block_size + position % block_size` — purely positional, no concept of reuse. For DMS, evicted token slots become available for new tokens. This requires a separate DMS-managed slot map that tracks free slots per head. The `DMSState` circular buffer would maintain this: when a token exits the window and is evicted, its slot index is pushed to a free list; new tokens pop from the free list instead of computing from position.
+
+5. **Per-head slot_mapping in reshape_and_cache kernel** — The Triton kernel `reshape_and_cache_kernel_flash` uses `slot_mapping[token_idx]` — one slot per token, shared across all heads. Per-head DMS needs `slot_mapping[token_idx, head_idx]` or equivalently `slot_mapping[token_idx * num_kv_heads + head_idx]`. Options:
+   - Extend the kernel with a `num_kv_heads` loop or second grid dimension to read per-head slot maps
+   - Batch×head trick at write time: reshape K/V to `(num_tokens * num_kv_heads, 1, head_dim)`, slot_mapping to `(num_tokens * num_kv_heads,)`, call existing kernel with head-flattened inputs
+   - Bypass the kernel for DMS writes and use `flash_attn_with_kvcache`'s built-in cache write via `cache_seqlens` (as Model Optimizer does)
+
+---
